T*
(There are only two ways to use LLMs in a computer program: as part of a pipeline, or as an) Tj
T*
(agent. In other words, either you express the control flow of the program in code, or you give) Tj
T*
(a LLM tools and allow it to manage the control flow itself 1 . Here?s how you might structure a) Tj
T*
(trivial ?summarize a bunch of information and email it to me? program as a pipeline: context =) Tj
T*
(gather_context \( various , data , sources \) llm_response = llm_summarize \( context \) summary =) Tj
T*
(parse \( llm_response \) email_me \( summary , my_email \) And here?s how you?d do it as an agent:) Tj
T*
(read_data_tool = build_read_data_tool \( various , data , sources \) email_tool =) Tj
T*
(build_email_tool \( my_email \) run_agent \( tools : [ read_data_tool , email_tool ] \) It?s like) Tj
T*
(the difference between a library and a framework. When you use a library, you define the) Tj
T*
(structure of the program yourself, and call out to various library helpers along the way. When) Tj
T*
(you use a framework, the main structure of the program lives in the framework, and it calls) Tj
T*
(your code at various points. There are tradeoffs involved in both approaches. Frameworks let) Tj
T*
(you get started more quickly and typically give you features ?for free?, but can be diffi...) Tj
T*
